9
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:35,159
To film his Napoléon, Abel Gance shot with several cameras, generating two different negatives and hence two original versions:

10
00:00:35,159 --> 00:00:38,320
one called "Opéra" (Premiered at the Opéra de Paris, 4 April 1927, 4 hours long)

11
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:43,520
the second called "Apollo" (presented to the press and the operators of the Apollo theater in May 1927, 9 hours and 30 minutes long).

12
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:47,520
Gance then established a final version from the Apollo negative alone, of a length of around 7 hours.

13
00:00:47,520 --> 00:00:53,439
It is on this definitive version called the "Grande Version" that the restoration carried out by La Cinémathèque française between 2015 and 2022 is based.

14
00:00:53,439 --> 00:00:59,520
The splitting of the film into two parts was carried out from the Abel Gance archives preserved at La Cinémathèque française and la Bibliothèque nationale de France.

15
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:06,319
It includes the final triptych called "Departure of the Army from Italy" according to the three-screen projection process conceived by Gance that he would later name "Polyvision".

16
00:01:06,439 --> 00:01:10,120
The reconstruction and restoration of images were carried out from elements preserved in the following archives:


17
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:15,280
La Cinémathèque française, Centre national du cinéma et de l'image animée, la Cinémathèque de Toulouse, la Cinémathèque royale de Belgique (Bruxelles),

18
