(Chuquet) (Hist.)

399
03:22:09,040 --> 03:22:13,959
“And tomorrow, my general,
you will sleep
in Toulon.”

400
03:24:32,719 --> 03:24:34,520
“Turn the guns.”

401
03:24:46,479 --> 03:24:54,760
The English canonmen
are being hacked to pices on their
guns. Of all those

402
03:24:54,760 --> 03:25:03,520
who defend the redoubt,
there is not one who has no
injury.
(Historical)

403
03:25:55,799 --> 03:25:59,520
The Attack of Little
Gibraltar.

404
03:26:53,559 --> 03:27:02,399
“This is nothing,
I already saw all this
at Brienne!
Bold Straw Nose!”

405
03:28:47,159 --> 03:28:53,559
The English general
O'Hara orders the
retreat.

406
03:29:50,719 --> 03:29:52,440
“Marcellin!”

407
03:30:57,200 --> 03:31:02,959
And in the middle of obscurity,
the rain, a terrible
wind, the disorder

408
03:31:02,959 --> 03:31:09,879
of cadavers, the screams of
the wounded and the dying,
we no longer shoot, we tackle

409
03:31:09,879 --> 03:31:15,879
each other hand to hand. No
other weapons than iron.
(Napoléon's Memoirs)

410
03:33:12,040 --> 03:33:16,280
“Go get me
this young captain
who has been fighting

411
03:33:16,280 --> 03:33:19,680
like a tiger for
two hours.”
(Historical)

412
03:33:54,000 --> 03:33:56,040
“Your name?”

413
03:33:57,879 --> 03:34:00,120
“Desaix.”

414
03:34:47,559 --> 03:34:51,399
“Take out
the English squadron...”

415
03:35:15,000 --> 03:35:21,600
“...and burn
the French squadron.”

416
03:35:47,559 --> 03:35:55,719
The French troops,
after 76 hours of
combat in the mud and
the storm, seized,

417
03:35:55,719 --> 03:36:03,040
at 4 in the morning, the
last English redoubt.
(Napoléon's Memoirs)

418
03:36:13,920 --> 03:36:19,719
“The drums?
Where are the drums
of the 6th?”

419
03:36:45,479 --> 03:36:48,680
“The drums?
Present!!”

420
03:36:51,000 --> 03:36:54,559
Fallen under gunfire, the
drums of the 6th were going

421
03:36:54,559 --> 03:36:58,600
to be replaced in their
task by an unforeseen
auxiliary...

422
03:37:03,760 --> 03:37:06,040
...hail.

423
03:38:22,360 --> 03:38:28,239
“I believe
that this man
will save France.”

424
03:38:48,159 --> 03:38:55,959
After the Victory.

425
03:39:59,319 --> 03:40:05,799
At dawn, from the top
of the Aiguillette, one of
the greatest spectacles

426
03:40:05,799 --> 03:40:12,600
that had struck the imagination
of Napoleon offered itself to
his view.
(Chuquet)

427
03:42:07,319 --> 03:42:13,959
“What... is the name of...
this captain?”

428
03:42:15,280 --> 03:42:18,520
“Napoléon Bonaparte.”

429
03:42:45,079 --> 03:42:52,959
At dawn, the commissioners
of the Armies who came to give
him, as a token of

430
03:42:52,959 --> 03:43:02,840
apology, the rank of brigadier
general, find him asleep,
his head on a drum.
(Historical)

431
03:43:32,639 --> 03:43:37,399
“Here is
the taker of Toulon!”
(Historical)

432
03:44:51,040 --> 03:44:55,840
End of the
First Part.

